	year = {2015},
	keywords = {brain connectivity, brain plasticity, complex systems, modularity theory, probabilistic epigenesis, psychometric g},
	abstract = {Abstract This chapter reviews current key questions, issues, and findings in the study of atypical cognitive development, as well as the history of earlier research on this topic. Key questions include (1) How general versus specific are the processes of cognitive development and individual differences in cognition? (2) What is the etiology of cognitive development and individual cognitive differences? (3) How do these etiologies act on structural and functional brain development? (4) How malleable are developmental and individual cognitive outcomes? and (5) How similar are the answers to these four questions in youth and aging? A key issue that runs throughout the chapter is the role of nature versus nurture in the development of physical and psychological forms. The resolution to this issue is found in the principles of probabilistic epigenesis, constructivism, and complex systems that self-organize to yield emergent properties. The chapter describes a multilevel, interdisciplinary approach that is needed to understand atypical cognitive development. Besides behavioral and cognitive development, these levels include (a) etiology (genetic and environmental influences and their interplay) and (b) brain mechanisms. Specific examples of atypical cognitive development are described to illustrate these levels of analysis and to address key issues. These examples include (a) amblyopia, (b) orphanage rearing, (c) three genetic syndromes that produce intellectual disability (i.e., Down syndrome, fragile X syndrome, and Williams syndrome; (d) early treated phenylketonuria; and (e) developmental dyslexia. The chapter concludes with a summary of current answers to the five key questions and implications for future research.}
}

